label chapter10:

    # [Scene: Rooftop Gardens & Micro-farms | Late morning — after a rain squall]

    scene bg ch10_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, rising acoustic rhythm — hand-drums and soft guitar]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Water trickling into a cistern; distant gulls; the steady slap of mismatched sneakers on wooden planks]
    "You shoulder the muddy jacket tighter and taste iron and salt in the air. The rain has left everything washed and honest: colors deepened, soil darker, the city relieved for a breath. Your hands know the"
    "path without instruction—lift, tilt, secure a hose clamp—because you've done this a dozen small times for a dozen people's small chances."

    "Elias 'Eli' Maren" "Gravity does all the work if you let it. Later we can teach the kids to trace the water like it's a map."
    show maya_calder at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_calder "They'll like that. Maps with puddles are less scary."

    "Elias 'Eli' Maren" "Less scary, more useful. I can write a little lesson—'Follow the Water, Find the Food.'"

    maya_calder "Make it rhyme and they'll remember it."
    "Your fingers close the final clamp on the gravity-fed cistern. Water shudders through a hose and fills the first drum with a soft, satisfied sigh. The system is simple and stubborn: gutters into barrels, into a"
    "sealed cistern, into a dripline that feeds three beds. It will not stop the ocean, but it will buy a family a week of salad, buy a child vitamin-rich greens through a storm, buy time."
    "Theo appears at the ladder with a tablet glowing in his hand, cheeks flushed from running the length of the block. His glasses are fogged a little at the edges; he hands you the tablet without preamble."
    show theo_baines at right:
        zoom 0.7

    theo_baines "I ran the corridor overlays against the flood risk model. I found pockets that stay above the worst projections for another three years—if we clear access and start those micro-welfare hubs now."

    maya_calder "Show me the corridor by the old bakery."

    theo_baines "Here—see these roofs? We can connect them with a line of shared tools and an emergency rota. If we formalize tenancy protections for the folks who open their attics, we can rotate people through higher ground when the tide spikes."

    maya_calder "The bakery's owner is Rosa's neighbor. If we ask her—"

    theo_baines "She'll want guarantees. Legal ones. Not just promises."

    maya_calder "You owe her more than promises. You owe her a plan that keeps nets and memory."

    menu:
        "Ask Theo to draft a simple tenancy memorandum now":
            "You tap the screen and say, 'Make it simple—two pages, plain language, a rotation schedule.' Theo nods, already rephrasing clauses in his head."
        "Put the legal paperwork on hold and go talk to Rosa first":
            "You fold the tablet closed and climb down the ladder toward the lane where Rosa mends nets. Theo frowns, but understands the cadence of your work: law must follow trust."

    # --- merge ---
    "Scene continues"
    "The rooftop smells like wet wood and compost and someone cutting citrus; everything is immediate and edible. Asha arrives with insulated boxes slung across her shoulder. Her scarf is bright against the slate sky, and she moves like someone who will not let hunger be the final word."
    show asha_patel at center:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_patel "We have volunteers for tonight's rotating kitchen. Two people can host on the high side of Market Row. I've got a van scheduled for tomorrow to ferry the elderly who want to try a temporary attic swap."

    maya_calder "Temporary attics are not exile; they are a lifeline, and the language matters. Can you make the outreach sound like—"

    asha_patel "Like a vacation? No. Like a neighborhood breathing room. I can do that."

    maya_calder "Breathing room. I like that."
    "Rosa's silhouette appears in the lane below, a patchwork of a lifetime in the way she carries herself. She climbs the ladder with slow, purposeful steps, carrying a small woven basket. Her hands are stained with"
    "rope fibers and the smell of brine clings to her. She surveys the rooftop with a look that is difficult to parse—pride, suspicion, something older."
    hide maya_calder
    show rosa_calder at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_calder "You think a bunch of roofs will keep the harbor?"
    hide theo_baines
    show maya_calder at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_calder "No. But they can feed people when the shipments stop, and give someone a dry place to sleep if the street floods."

    rosa_calder "When my mother tied the nets she didn't call it resilience. She called it life. Don't let them take the word from us and turn it into numbers."

    maya_calder "I won't. We won't let them make our story only about mathematics."
    "Rosa looks at you—there is warmth, and a threading caution—complex and readable in pieces. You do not know whether she's afraid you'll forget the docks or that you'll lock yourselves into something that looks like salvation"
    "but smells like displacement. The ambiguity sits between you and becomes a fuel, not a wall."

    menu:
        "Invite Rosa to run a seed-exchange table tonight":
            "She lifts a brow, surprised, and then hums. 'Seeds are a language,' she says. 'I suppose I could teach a few words.'"
        "Ask Rosa to tell one old dock story during the lantern circle instead":
            "Rosa taps the edge of the barrel, thinking, and finally nods. 'A story stirs memory better than a pamphlet,' she mutters."

    # --- merge ---
    "Scene continues"
    "As afternoon moves toward gold, you plant a row of fast greens in recycled crates. Your palms press compost into the beds; the dirt clings under your nails like an honest confession. People drift across the"
    "rooftop—neighbors carrying jars to trade, kids tallying worms like found treasure, Elias 'Eli' Maren balancing a crate of seedlings and a scrap of canvas he plans to turn into a teaching banner."

    "Elias 'Eli' Maren" "Tonight, when you talk to the group, don't lead with lists. Lead with a small thing—how to keep a sprout alive. Hope grows from simple competence."

    maya_calder "Okay. We'll show them a living proof tonight: one bed, one week of yields, one rota. Then we'll ask them what they'd want next."
    "Theo pulls you aside and points to the tablet, his finger hovering at a series of notes flagged 'ethics' and 'data ownership'."
    hide asha_patel
    show theo_baines at center:
        zoom 0.7

    theo_baines "If we aggregate who moves where for safety, we need to lock that data down. People won't sign unless they trust us. I can code anonymization, but we need a governance pledge—community oversight."

    maya_calder "We'll write it into the hub charter. Community oversight, rotating roles, a simple complaint ladder. No external database without consent."

    theo_baines "Good. Also—Sienna's office pushed up their seawall timeline. I saw the notice. They're mobilizing contractors next quarter."
    "You feel the name like a wind from another species: institutional, precise. Sienna's plan is an engine that will not stop for neighborhoods. It will protect large tracts but flatten the small stitches of life you"
    "are quilting. You do not waste the scolding; you save the fuel for making alternatives tangible."

    maya_calder "They'll move fast."

    theo_baines "Then we move faster in different ways. If the city builds what they plan, at least we'll have models people can touch: food, shelter, skills."
    hide rosa_calder
    show asha_patel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_patel "Tonight's workshop will be hands-on. We'll teach water capture, then a session on quick reinforcement for attics—simple braces, tarps, how to anchor a door against surge. People need confidence as much as charts."

    maya_calder "Community-run hubs that double as livelihood centers—garden-to-table training, tool libraries, tenancy templates, a kitchen rota. They are physical promises."

    menu:
        "Draw up the first hub charter with Theo now":
            "You and Theo sit cross-legged on the rooftop, drafting articles and scribbling priorities until the page looks like a small, practical constitution."
        "Wait until the lantern circle to co-create with neighbors":
            "You tuck your notebook away and decide the first words should be theirs. The waiting feels strategic, like leaving room for breath."

    # --- merge ---
    "Scene continues"
    "Evening settles soft and full. String lanterns blink on, reflected in the wet wood. Elias 'Eli' Maren taps a scrap drum and the rooftop answers—rhythms like a pulse. People form a rough circle, damp coats and"
    "bright scarves and palms that smell of compost and bread. Someone hands you a chipped mug of soup. You take it with trembling gratitude for the ordinary miracle of warmth."

    "Elias 'Eli' Maren" "For every bed we plant, we get a chance to teach someone how to keep something alive. For every attic we secure, we promise shelter."

    maya_calder "We are not denying the seawall exists. We are making a web of small, stubborn places that keep people fed and safe while the big machines decide their timelines. We will teach, rotate, protect data, and make sure the promises are legal. We will not let memory be drowned."
    "Neighbors murmur; a woman whose roof you repaired last week squeezes your shoulder. Theo passes around printed maps marked with corridor routes and hub locations; Asha announces volunteer slots for the rotating kitchen; Rosa volunteers to run a seed-exchange table at the market."
    "Somewhere in the murmur, a text buzzes in Theo's pocket—an update from the resilience authority. He glances at you: there's no scandal in his face, only a steady will."

    theo_baines "Contractors booked. Sienna is accelerating. They want to begin physical works faster than they told us."

    maya_calder "Then we begin not to stop. Not to argue with the tide, but to plant islands."
    "You close your eyes for a beat and feel the rooftop settle around you like a promise kept small and large at once—hands in dirt, lamp-glow, a drumbeat that has nothing to do with policy memos"
    "and everything to do with heartbeat. The pockets of safety you sew are simple and stubborn and human; they will not save the whole city, but they will hold the people in it while other battles"
    "are fought."
    "You think of the next steps—formal tenancy protections to present at the council, the legal appendix Theo will draft, Asha's van schedule, Rosa's seed list, a draft of the hub charter sketched on a napkin. There is momentum, palpable and warm, and the work feels like hope with calluses."
    "A single thought threads through all of it: the city might change, but you can choose how to change it."
    "You lift your hands from the soil and, beneath the lantern light, feel the choice of how to care expand in your chest—how much to lean into legal scaffolding, how much to leave open to people's"
    "improvisation, how far to push volunteers before they burn. The options are many and urgent, but tonight is not the night to decide all of them. Tonight you have sown proof: if people can taste the"
    "lettuce grown by their own hands, they will fight for the bed."
    "(Page-turn thought: You run your thumb over the braid of leather at your wrist and let the rhythm of the drum match the rhythm of your breath. There's a fragile plan on your table, a crowd"
    "that will show up, and a bureaucratic machine moving faster than you hoped. The choices are close; the next steps will require not only strategy but care. But for the first time since the tide maps"
    "first came across your desk, you can picture a neighborhood that keeps breathing.)"
    hide maya_calder
    hide theo_baines
    hide asha_patel

